@leventov Nevermind, it looks like that's fine, since it does this already:

```java
    int cardinality = selector.getValueCardinality();
    BitSet valueIds = new BitSet(cardinality);
    for (int i = 0; i < cardinality; i++) {
      if (predicate.apply(selector.lookupName(i))) {
        valueIds.set(i);
      }
    }
```

getValueCardinality is the same as maxId for this selector, so any bits past maxId will already be false.

@kaijianding The contract is there because it enables optimizations that need to be able to read the dictionary ahead of time. For example, ValueMatchers can use it to build a set of ids matching a predicate before scanning, and then use that set during the scan for filtering (instead of actually applying the predicate to each row). TopN can use it to pre-allocate storage for each possible dimension value. Filtered DimensionSpecs can use it to build an id mapping ahead of time. If DimensionSelector `getRow()` could return ids beyond what `getValueCardinality()` returns when the selector is first created, then applying these optimizations could lead to incorrect results.

Of course, the current solution to that problem (pretending the values are null) isn't perfect either: it leads to the issue you're facing now, where nulls show up in unexpected places.

One way to solve both problems is to return `CARDINALITY_UNKNOWN` from `getValueCardinality()` of StringDimensionIndexer's DimensionSelector and also remove the maxId limit. This would tell callers that the dictionary isn't known ahead of time and disable the above optimizations. I'm not sure if this would be worth the performance hit or not.

Another is on the query end: if you add a filter like the following to your query, then (after the patch from this PR is applied) you won't get unexpected nulls in `myDim`.

```java
{
  "type": "not",
  "field": {
    "type": "selector",
    "dimension": "myDim",
    "value": ""
  }
}
```

Another option is to change the contract of DimensionSelector such that `getRow()` _can_ return values outside `getValueCardinality()`, and it's up to the caller to decide what it wants to do. Perhaps topN and groupBy would decide to skip over such values and not include them in the results.

